VThe M. A. Hanna Company, a specialty chemical company, agreed yesterday to sell most of its Cadillac Plastic shapes distribution and fabrication businesses to GE Plastics, a unit of the General Electric Company. Cadillac Plastic posted sales last year of $378 million from distributing and making plastic sheet, rod, tube and film. Financial terms of the transaction were not disclosed. M. A. Hanna said that nearly all of the assets and leased facilities of Cadillac Plastic in North America, Asia, Britain and the Netherlands would be part of the sale, but that the sale did not include the Richmond Aircraft unit, and three joint ventures in Germany, France and Spain.
p33
aVMoving to offer digital television service throughout the Southeast, BellSouth intends to announce today that it has signed a long-term contract to purchase satellite services from General Electric, an executive close to the deal said yesterday. BellSouth had been rumored to be in discussions with Loral Space and Communications, a G.E. rival in the satellite industry.
p34
aVEARNINGS reports have been coming up rosier than ever for the first quarter of 2000 -- up about 20 percent from the corresponding period last year. As a result, many market strategists believe that stocks will soon resume a steady upward climb. But there is growing concern among some accounting professionals that many companies are relying on financial alchemy to burnish their results.
p35
aVRIGHT now, Cisco Systems seems as close to perfect as a technology company can be. The biggest maker of Internet communications equipment, Cisco is also the second-most valuable company in the nation, after General Electric. It has succeeded in elevating its chief executive, John Chambers, to near-deity status in some quarters, and has even managed to stay in the government's good graces, in contrast to Microsoft, among others.
p36
aVIt may be months before the Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, but the network that will broadcast the games, NBC, is starting a promotional campaign.
p37
aVErnst & Young L.L.P. has agreed to combine with a prominent Washington lobbying company, Washington Counsel P.C., to create a new lobbying unit separate from the Ernst tax department. Washington Counsel, which reported $8.3 million in lobbying fees last year, represents Charles Schwab, Merrill Lynch, Hewlett-Packard, General Electric, Ford and Aetna.
p38
aVAmtran Inc., parent of the discount carrier American Trans Air Inc., has ordered 47 jetliners from the Boeing Company valued at $2.9 billion to replace aging aircraft and expand its fleet. The order includes 37 of Boeing's 737-800 jetliners and 10 of the 757-300's, partly financed by Boeing's capital arm and two leasing companies. Amtran, which flies under the name ATA to 27 United States cities from hubs in Chicago and Indianapolis, will lease 17 of the 737-800's from aircraft lessors and purchase the other 30 planes from Boeing.
p39
aVInternational Paper Wins Contest to Buy Champion International Paper emerged the victor in a bidding war to acquire Champion International after a Finnish paper company declined to increase its offer. International Paper agreed to pay about $7.3 billion, or $75 a share in cash and stock. UPM of Finland had reached a merger deal with Champion in February for $6.6 billion, or $56.50 a share. International Paper made a surprise cash-and-stock bid of $64 a share two weeks ago. UPM raised its bid to $70 in cash, but failed to match International's highest offer as the deadline passed. [Page C4.]
p40
aVComputer Virus Is Traced To Apartment in Philippines More than a dozen law enforcement agents raided a Manila apartment from which they said a malicious computer program was unleashed last week, disrupting computer systems around the world. They took one resident into custody and ordered his roommate, a woman, to turn herself in. The agents, including two representing the Federal Bureau of Investigation, apparently expected to find the computer from which the attack was started. A local official said that no computer was found, but that a box containing 17 items including telephones, wires, computer disks and computer magazines was seized. The officials would not say what had led them to the apartment and did not characterize the moves as arrests. [Page A1.]
p41
aVJeff Colborn plunged into fusion energy research in the late 1980's, first at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory and then at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, filled with idealism about fusion's potential for revolutionizing nuclear power generation. ''I wanted the toughest challenge,'' said Mr. Colborn, recalling the goals he had after studying engineering and physics at the University of California at Berkeley.
