VThe General Electric Company announced yesterday that it would lay off more than 500 workers from its plant in Louisville, Ky. The company refused to give an exact number of employees that would be let go. But union officials estimated that the number would be between 500 and 800. Many of the layoffs would come from a group of 1,100 hired two years ago.
p81
aVThe Fonar Corporation was awarded $110.5 million yesterday by a Federal jury that concluded the General Electic Company infringed two patents covering magnetic resonance imaging technology. The award, if upheld, would provide a big financial lift for Fonar, based in Melville, L.I. The company posted sales of $15.4 million last year. G.E. said it would file a motion asking Judge Leonard Wexler to overturn the verdict. G.E. was found liable for infringement last week after a three-week trial.
p82
aVJohn F. Welch, the chairman of the General Electric Company, underwent open-heart surgery to relieve a blocked heart artery, the company said today. Mr. Welch, 59, had the surgery Friday at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston. He is expected to resume a normal work schedule in three to four weeks, the company said. The operation -- in which part of a blood vessel is used to bypass the damaged artery -- was done less than two weeks after Mr. Welch had an angioplasty to clear a blocked artery.
p83
aVThe Fonar Corporation won a Federal jury verdict on Friday in a patent trial against the General Electric Company. The decision could provide a big financial lift for Fonar, a tiny maker of magnetic resonance imaging machines. A jury in United States District Court in Hauppauge concluded that General Electric had infringed both the Fonar patents that were in dispute. Fonar, which is based in Melville, L.I., and had sales of $15.4 million last year, is seeking $300 million in damages. The portion of the trial to determine damages is expected to begin this week.
p84
aVThe International Business Machines Corporation agreed yesterday to buy GE Capital's computer maintenance unit. The purchase price was not disclosed, although individuals familiar with the properties estimated that they would sell for $50 million to $100 million. I.B.M. said the purchase would help expand its computer maintenance business. GE Capital Systems Support Services, which is based in Atlanta, employs 1,300. I.B.M. has not determined how many it will keep. GE Capital, the financial services unit of the General Electric Compnay, said the unit up for sale was one of eight technology-management businesses owned by GE Capital. Together, the eight units had $1.2 billion revenue in 1994, a G.E. spokesman said.
p85
aVThe Kemper Corporation said yesterday that its planned sale to Zurich Insurance and a group of investors would be completed Monday, a week later than expected. Zurich Insurance said its $2 billion purchase of the financial services company was delayed to complete documents relating to the sale. Kemper put itself up for sale last year after spurning an offer of $2.4 billion from the General Electric Company. It then agreed to be acquired by Conseco Inc. for $3.25 billion, but the deal fell through after Conseco failed to obtain financing. Zurich Insurance's offer values Kemper at $49.50 a share in cash and securities.
p86
aVShares of King World Productions surged nearly 5 percent yesterday after the Turner Broadcasting System was reported to have had discussions to acquire the company in a $1.9 billion stock swap. But executives close to the talks cautioned that the two companies have held negotiations with a number of potential merger partners, including each other, for months, and that nothing was imminent. King World stock rose $2, to $42.875, on the New York Stock Exchange, where more than 588,000 shares changed hands, five times its average daily volume in the last three months.
