VThe General Electric Company announced nearly 2,000 job cuts yesterday in its Power Systems division, saying the action was prompted by a slowdown in the worldwide market for gas and steam turbines. A restructuring plan will cut about 950 salaried and 1,000 hourly workers worldwide, a spokesman, Leonard K. Doviak, said. Of those, 980 reductions will be made in Schenectady, N.Y., the Power Systems headquarters. Another 350 cuts will be made in Greenville, S.C., and 620 cuts will be made at sales and service operations in Europe and Asia. The jobs will disappear over the next six months through voluntary terminations, early retirement incentives and layoffs, the company said. The Power Systems division employs about 25,000 people.
