aVThe merger agreement announced last night by the General Electric Company and the RCA Corporation would rejoin two companies that fueled each other's growth from the closing days of World War I and then diverged as each became giants of burgeoning communications, space technology and electronics industries. For nearly four decades, until the dawn of the computer age, the two companies were the symbols of American high technology. And in recent years, both have undergone wide-ranging and often painful revampings to try to regain an edge they slowly lost to unexpected foreign competition, particularly from Japan. It was General Electric, founded by Thomas Alva Edison and the inheritor of his incandescent lamp technology, that at the urging of the President Wilson played a key role in the formation of the Radio Corporation of America in 1919. The company was forged out of the assets of the American Marconi Corporation, makers of wireless receivers, to establish an American presence in the fledgling communications business.
