VA group of shareholders of the former Rockefeller Center Properties Inc. has filed a lawsuit charging that David Rockefeller, Goldman, Sachs and others committed securities fraud in their $1.2 billion purchase of the company earlier this year. The suit contends that Mr. Rockefeller, Goldman, Sachs and the company's management knew but did not tell shareholders that the buyers were in talks to sell to the General Electric Company's NBC unit the space the broadcaster leases in the New York landmark, Rockefeller Center, for $440 million. As a result, shareholders were forced to sell their stakes at an artificially low price, the suit says. The sale of the company was approved by shareholders before the Rockefeller-Goldman group reached the agreement with NBC. The defendants called the suit meritless. The suit, filed yesterday in Federal court in Delaware, seeks unspecified damages or rescission of the sale.
