VThe General Electric Company said yesterday that it would cut about 1,200 jobs in a revamping of its GE Power Systems subsidiary, which makes turbines and other power-plant equipment. The cuts, which amount to 5 percent of the unit's work force, are expected to take place early next year. G.E. plans to contract with other companies to manufacture steam turbine parts from its plant in Schenectady, N.Y., eliminating about 475 jobs. In addition, G.E. will move its sales and services operations from there to Atlanta, which will affect 450 employees. G.E. also announced plans to close a steam turbine factory in Fitchburg, Mass., which will eliminate up to 600 jobs. GE Power Systems has 24,000 workers.
