aVMANAGEMENT theorists, who have created clunky terms like ''co-opetition,'' are generally not known for their elegance with language. That's not likely to change anytime soon, considering the buzzword now sweeping through corner offices around the country: BHAG's, for ''big, hairy, audacious goals.'' A BHAG (pronounced BEE-hag) is supposed to inspire an organization to reach for a goal it might otherwise think impossible, as when NASA set out to land a man on the moon in the 1960's. In management circles, the notion was refined by Gary Hamel and C. K. Prahalad, who observed in a 1989 article in The Harvard Business Review that companies that emerged as global leaders had invariably begun with outsized ambitions.
