(lp517
VF.D.A. REJECTS WYETH DRUG Wyeth's new schizophrenia drug was rejected by the Food and Drug Administration because it was not shown to be effective. Shares of Wyeth and its partner, Solvay of Belgium, dropped. Wyeth said the F.D.A. needed more data showing that the medicine, bifeprunox, works before the agency would consider approval. The F.D.A. also requested information on a patient who died while taking the drug. The drug does not cause weight gain, a safety concern with other schizophrenia remedies, but studies have also shown it is less effective than Zyprexa from Eli Lilly and Risperdal from Johnson & Johnson. ''Bifeprunox didn't work as well as Risperdal and Zyprexa in studies, and I can't see much reason to use this drug once generics of the others are available,'' said Michael Krensavage, an analyst with Raymond James in New York. Cheaper copies of Risperdal will be available next year, followed by generic Zyprexa in 2011. Shares of Wyeth, based in Madison, N.J., dropped $2.99, closing at $46.59. (BLOOMBERG NEWS)
