VACCOUNTING INQUIRY AT G.E. General Electric has terminated the employment of some workers at its rail unit after finding that they intentionally booked revenues for locomotive sales earlier than they should have, the company said. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, G.E. said it discovered the improprieties after the S.E.C. requested information about transactions at the rail unit between 2000 and 2003. ''Revenues had been inappropriately accelerated so that they were recognized in the fourth quarter of each of the years 2000 through 2003 rather than in the first quarter of the following year,'' the company said in the filing. A G.E. spokesman, Russell Wilkerson, said that ''a few'' employees had been involved in the problem, but declined to provide a precise figure. (REUTERS) JUDGE ALLOWS LASALLE BANK SALE
