aVDIABETES DRUG IS QUESTIONED -- An article in The New England Journal of Medicine raises safety questions about the GlaxoSmithKline diabetes pill Avandia while also restarting debate over the quality of work by federal drug regulators. [Page C1.] TAINTED TOOTHPASTE -- Chinese authorities are investigating two companies after toothpaste exported to Latin America was found to be tainted with diethylene glycol, an industrial solvent and prime ingredient in some antifreeze fluid. [C1.] PAY ATTENTION, PLEASE -- Viacom, the media conglomerate that owns cable networks like MTV and Comedy Central, says it has devised new formats to try to keep its young viewers glued to the television set when the commercials are appearing. ''They're younger, they're more quickly engaged and more quickly dismissive if they're not engaged,'' said Judy McGrath, above, chairman and chief executive of MTV Networks. [C6.] BIG-BOY LETTERS ARE CHALLENGED -- Correspondence among investors known as big-boy letters are widely used and represent a private contract among presumably sophisticated investors. Now they face a legal challenge. [C1.] WHAT'S KERKORIAN UP TO? -- The latest Securities and Exchange Commission filing by the Tracinda Corporation, the billionaire financier Kirk Kerkorian's holding company, has analysts wondering if this is the opening move in a plan to take the MGM company private. [C1.] TRADE ISSUES WITH CHINA -- As the senior trade officials for United States and China begin talks, some question whether the Bush administration's efforts to open China to American goods can satisfy a Congress irate over a trade deficit with China that rose to $232 billion last year. [C1.] IDEA FROM GOOGLE: AN AUCTION -- Google has proposed that the Federal Communications Commission allocate radio spectrum employing the same kind of auction that the search engine company now uses in selling advertisements to create more competition among cable companies and Internet service providers. [C10.] MYSPACE EXPOSES SEX OFFENDERS -- MySpace, the popular social networking site, has agreed to provide authorities in all 50 states with the names, addresses and online profiles of thousands of known convicted sexual offenders who have opened up accounts on its service. [C8.] LOWE'S PROFIT MISSES MARK -- The Lowe's Company, the No. 2 home improvement chain behind Home Depot, reported a lower-than-expected first-quarter profit and has cut its full-year earnings outlook. [C7.] COURT TO HEAR BOND CASE -- The Supreme Court has agreed to rule on important tax issues involving interest and taxes on municipal bonds in a case with the potential to change the market for such bonds. [C3.] MOVIE MAY ENLIVEN DEBATE -- Insurance industry officials and health policy experts suggest that Michael Moore's movie on the American health care system is likely to provoke debate, not radical change. [C3.] EMI GROUP SALE WINS SUPPORT -- The board at the music giant EMI Group has decided to support a new $4.7 billion offer from a private British investor, Terra Firma Capital Partners. [C3.] JUST LOOKING FOR A RETURN -- The Chinese government's $3 billion purchase of a nonvoting stake in the Blackstone Group was simply a way to raise returns on overseas investments, a Chinese official says. [C4.] CLINTON BOOKS DUE EARLIER -- The publishers of two rival biographies of Hillary Rodham Clinton have moved up their on-sale dates once again to the first week in June in a game of publishing one-upmanship. [C3.] RETRIAL FOR BROKERS -- The United States attorney's office in Brooklyn said it would retry former brokers for Citigroup, Merrill Lynch and Lehman Brothers on charges that they conspired to commit fraud by allowing day traders to eavesdrop on orders made through internal squawk boxes. [C11.] TAX GETS SCRUTINY -- A tax originally intended to ensure that rich investors did not live tax-free is not working as planned, the Joint Committee on Taxation says. But a nonpartisan tax group has a solution. [C2.] SAUDIS BUY G.E. PLASTICS UNIT -- General Electric agreed yesterday to sell its plastics division for $11.6 billion to the largest public company in Saudi Arabia, the Saudi Basic Industries Corporation known as Sabic. Jeffrey R. Immelt, the chief executive of G.E., said the deal would transform the industry by combining Sabic's low-cost materials and global reach with G.E.'s strong marketing and technology. [C8.] YOU'RE FIRED -- A new study examining turnover among top executives has found that corporate boards were more than three times as likely to dismiss failing chief executives as they were a decade ago. [C6.] LUGGAGE-FREE TRAVEL -- Some executives are shipping their bags ahead when they travel on business -- picking luggage up at their hotel, not an airport. And more businesses are providing these services. [C9.] ONLINE RETIREMENT -- As life spans lengthen, experts on aging say it is more important than ever to prepare for the physical and psychological aspects of retirement. A special section is at nytimes.com/retirement. BUSINESS OF GREEN -- The International Herald Tribune provides a global dialogue on the environment at nytimes.com/blogs. And The Times has a special section on the environment as a business at nytimes.com/business.
