TE-PALMOLIVE, the consumer products company, said that its first-quarter profit rose 50 percent, driven by sales of new products and growth in all geographic regions. (AP) QUALCOMM POSTED a 22 percent increase in profit in its fiscal second quarter on strong sales of chips for cellphones. (AP) GENERAL DYNAMICS AND RAYTHEON posted modestly higher first-quarter earnings, beating Wall Street's expectations, but were reluctant to raise their profit outlooks for the full year, citing unusually high uncertainty over future Pentagon financing. (AP) UNITED PARCEL SERVICE reported lower quarterly profit as a result of a charge related to aging aircraft and expenses for a voluntary layoff program. (REUTERS) HIGHER BEER PRICES, fewer discounts and another strong showing overseas offset sluggish United States sales for Anheuser-Busch, which reported a 3.7 percent increase in first-quarter earnings. (REUTERS) CORNING, THE SPECIALTY glass maker, said that quarterly profit rose 27 percent on better-than-expected demand for telecommunications products, sending its shares up more than 7 percent. (REUTERS) JEFFREY R. IMMELT, the chairman and chief of General Electric, said that he found the lagging performance of the company's shares ''frustrating.'' (REUTERS)
