VThe General Electric Company said yesterday that profits rose 9.6 percent in the first quarter, led by a strong performance at its financial unit, GE Capital Services. The unit's net income was up 22 percent in the quarter, compared with a year ago. John F. Welch Jr., G.E.'s chairman, cited double-digit earnings gains in six of the company's 12 businesses -- NBC, appliances, locomotives, motors, power systems and plastics. But pretax profits were sharply lower in the aircraft engines unit. The drop was attributed to product-development costs and a charge for previously announced layoffs as orders dried up from airlines.
