aVThe fight for Paramount Communications Inc. is a reminder of better times for Wall Street's takeover speculators, a group that since the hectic, epically profitable days of the 1980's has either evolved or withered away. Stock arbitragers rode the crest of that decade's merger and acquisition wave but found their ranks dwindling after the stock market crashed in October 1987. And two years after that, their business took a nearly fatal blow when the financing went awry on a leveraged buyout of the UAL Corporation. The collapse of that deal took other merger stocks -- and many arbitragers -- down with it.
