aNaNaVB y STEVEN J. MARCUS David I. Smith has worked for the General Electric Company for more than 40 years. Employed at the Transportation Systems division in Erie, Pa., he is an expert on the diagnosis and repair of locomotives and is considered one of the company's top field-service engineers. But Mr. Smith's expertise is a scarce resource. His help is often needed in many different places at once, and he is in great demand, far in excess of his availability, for training young engineers across the country. When Mr. Smith retires, moreover, his knowledge would normally leave the company with him.
p707
aVIN March 1977, brokers across the nation began hawking bonds to build two nuclear power plants in the State of Washington. The initial issue of $145 million, like most ''munis,'' sold well because of its tax-free interest income and its presumed safety. This ritual was re-enacted 13 more times, and by the spring of 1981, the Washington Public Power Supply System had sold $2.25 billion in bonds for the two plants. Major Wall Street investment houses, in the time-honored tradition of underwriting, bought the bonds and resold them at a profit, frequently to small investors who were saving for retirement and considered the paper gilt-edged. While the bond sales were taking place, however, basic questions were being raised about the economic viability of the power plants. One warning, in fact, was sounded by the Seattle City Council before the first bond was ever sold, when it decided not to be a customer for the electricity that the two nuclear plants were to produce. The decision was based on a detailed study that said demand for electricity in the Northwest could be met through conservation and simpler power plants.
