p713
(lp714
NaNaVIN this age of high technology, the way electricity is produced remains relatively primitive. ''It's comparable to how we used to calculate before we had computers,'' says Jack T. Brown, manager of Advanced Energy Conversion Systems at the Westinghouse Electric Corporation. But with a ceramic tube the size of a policeman's nightstick, he and his colleagues plan to revolutionize the generation and distribution of energy. The tube is the basic unit of a new design for fuel cells, which are battery-like devices that generate electricity from gaseous fuels without having to burn them. In contrast to the usual electromechanical ways of producing largescale electricity - boiling water to drive generators - fuel cells are based on electrochemistry: The combination of the reactants (the fuel) and oxidants (from the air), facilitated by the fuel cell's materials, emits electrons that produce electricity.
p715
