aVA spotless, light beige carpet stretches like a sea of tranquillity across the executive floor of the Morgan Bank. The walls are paneled in genuine, not-too-highly-polished oak. The baseboards are of green marble. Huge oil portraits of Morgan's past chairmen peer across the chamber from gilt frames. An antique grandfather clock, with wood inlay, quietly ticks away the hours. This perception of orderliness and this aura of perfection are the trademarks of the House of Morgan and of its two primary components - J.P. Morgan & Company, the holding company, and the Morgan Guaranty Trust Company, the bank. Morgan is so well run and so profitable that it is the paragon of the banking industry. Bankers Trust openly tries to emulate it, and even Walter B. Wriston, Citicorp's supremely self-confident chairman, often uses Morgan as a model of profitability and a yardstick by which to measure how well a bank is run. Last year, for example, Morgan - the nation's fifth-largest bank holding company with assets of $58.6 billion - earned 78 cents on each $100 of average assets, more than any other of the 15 largest bank holding companies.
