aVI T was designed as a minicomputer; it was sold as a minicomputer and it carried the price of a minicomputer. But it sure didn't perform like a minicomputer!'' That's how Kenneth G. Fisher recalled his reaction to the computer product that he inherited upon joining Prime Computer Inc. as its president five years ago. Back then, Prime was plagued by losses and Mr. Fisher, who had been working with big computers for 15 years, first at General Electric, then at Honeywell, quickly saw that the Prime machine could deliver power and performance akin to that of larger, so-called mainframe computers. Mr. Fisher also perceived a new computer market aborning, comprised of frustrated engineers and other technical people who could not get time on their company's overcrowded central computer. Out of such observations, Mr. Fisher then conceived a corporate strategy embracing all of a company's operations - marketing, product development, financial management, manufacturing and so on. The result was nothing less than to transform this floundering, fledgling company - and to fashion yet another legendary story within the computer industry.
