aVWhen a corporation's balance sheet is awash in red ink, how does it stay afloat? Pretty much the same way a household would when faced with expenses that exceed income - by cutting back where possible and borrowing the rest. That is precisely the situation that the nation's Big Three auto makers find themselves in now. The General Motors Corporation, the Ford Motor Company and the Chrysler Corporation have reported a staggering aggregate loss of more than $3.5 billion in the first nine months of this year, some $500 million more than most analysts had expected them to lose for the entire year.
