VThe Avista Corporation, a utility owner in the Northwest, and the Portland General Electric unit of Enron received subpoenas from the Commodity Futures Trading Commission seeking records on ''wash'' trades. The commission asked Avista and Portland General Electric for records dating to January 2000, spokesmen for the companies said. In wash or round-trip trades, companies simultaneously buy and sell power or natural gas at the same price. The trades can be used to increase trading volume or revenue. The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, the Securities and Exchange Commission and other agencies have been investigating energy companies' trading practices after Enron sought bankruptcy protection in December.
