aVR. H. Macy & Company, seeking to repay its debt, said yesterday that it planned to sell up to $150 million of its equity to its outside investors. Four large investors have agreed to buy about $100 million of equity. They are General Electric Capital Corporation, the largest outside investor, which already owns 24.6 percent of Macy's preferred stock; the Loews Corporation, which has 14.8 percent; Mutual Series Fund Inc., which owns 12.8 percent, and Taubman Investment Company, which has 5 percent.
p1302
aVThe British Government today began the selloff of its electricity industry in its largest privatization in 10 years. The Government expects to raise $10.2 billion in the stock offering. The 2.16 billion shares will sell for 240 pence, or about $4.73, each, or a total $:5.18 billion, the Government said. The offering caps Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's privatization program, which has so far raised $65 billion through the sales of Britain's telephone, gas and water utilities, as well as British Airways P.L.C. and other companies. Some nervousness has arisen about how successful the recent privatizations will be, with an uneasy stock market, the continuing Middle East crisis and the struggle for leadership within Britain's governing Conservative Party. Investors also remember the sale of the Government's third of the British Petroleum Company, which flopped because it coincided with the October 1987 stock market crash. But the Energy Secretary, John Wakeham, said 7.3 million people had registered an interest in buying the electric utility shares, second only to the record 7.5 million registrations for British Gas P.L.C. The Government has also calmed jitters about the offering by saying that it would cancel the sale if war broke out in the Persian Gulf. "I think in today's market conditions the offer will be a success," said Chris Rowland, an analyst with Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd. The Government signaled its intention to sell 100 percent of each of the 12 regional electricity companies of England and Wales. It had been considering whether to scale back the offer to 60 percent if market conditions were poor. The shares are expected to fetch a 20 percent premium when trading begins on Dec. 11. The application deadline is Dec. 5. Shareholders are to receive an average dividend return of 8.4 percent in the first year, Mr. Wakeham said. The Government has sought to enhance the complex sale with an installment payment plan of nearly two years, the longest ever, and with bonus shares and discounts on electricity bills, the types of perquisites it has offered in the past. The Government said at least 34 percent of the shares would be reserved for the general public in Britain, 20 percent would be available to foreign investors and the remaining 46 percent would go to British institutional investors. If heavy British demand for the shares occur, the 20 percent to be offered to foreign investors will be reduced, the Government said.
