aVMCA Inc., the parent company of Universal Studios and MCA Records, has enlisted some of Washington's heavy hitters to promote its possible sale to the Matsushita Electric Company, Japan's largest electronics company. The entertainment company, known for its political connections, has a board that includes both Robert S. Strauss, former chairman of the Democratic National Committee and a United States trade representative, and former Senator Howard H. Baker, who served as Senate Republican leader and President Reagan's chief of staff. The company's lobbyists include Jody Powell, President Carter's press secretary, and Anne Wexler, the public liaison in the Carter White House. Taking Swift Action Their mission is to overcome possible political objections to the MCA-Matsushita deal by critics who might argue that it involves the sale of a national resource to a foreign predator. The sales of CBS Records and, later, Columbia Studios to the Sony Corporation were criticized in some quarters on those grounds. MCA's strategy has been to act swiftly, portraying the proposal as a way of providing the money the company needs for global expansion.
