p1373
aVWhenever the nation's top corporate executives are asked who is the best manager among them, Charles F. Knight, the 50-year-old chairman and chief executive officer of the Emerson Electric Company, ranks in the top five. Mr. Knight has earned the respect of his peers even though he is not a highly visible superstar like Lee A. Iacocca. Instead, he has won high marks by quietly racking up year after year of record performance. His company - which makes electric items from power saws to microchip pressure sensors - has had record earnings 28 years in a row, the last 13 under his stewardship. To keep the string going, Mr. Knight relies on more strategies than most managers: He has stressed development of new products, moving the St. Louis-based company (which is unrelated to the much-smaller Emerson Radio Corporation) to the cutting edge of high-tech manufacturing. He pursues acquisitions, having bought more than a dozen companies in the last two years. And he pushes Emerson's 60 division heads to keep costs down.
