aVThe Air Force announced today that it had suspended the General Electric Company from future Pentagon contracts because of the company's indictment earlier this week on charges that it falsified claims and lied to the Government about work on a nuclear warhead system. The temporary debarment, announced by Air Force Secretary Verne Orr, was the first such action ever taken against a major Defense Department supplier. G.E. is the nation's fourth-largest military contractor. The Air Force also requested $208 million in voluntary refunds from General Electric and the Pratt & Whitney division of the United Technologies Corporation for making greater-than- expected profits on contracts for supplies of aircraft engine spare parts. Intensified Crackdown Today's actions reflect an intensification of the Defense Department's crackdown on the growing problem of its errant contractors. (Page D4.)
p1482
aVThe Defense Department's crackdown on its errant contractors reached a new point of intensity today when the General Electric Company was temporarily barred from getting more of the Pentagon's business and refunds were demanded from it and the Pratt & Whitney division of the United Technologies Corporation. What began about three years ago with the slapping of the wrists of small companies caught defrauding the Government or wasting the taxpayer's money has escalated into more punitive measures against some of the largest makers of weapons in the land. The reason? Verne Orr, the Secretary of the Air Force, stated it succinctly today: ''National support for building military strength has been severely battered by public perception that we pay too much for the goods and services we acquire.'' 'Significantly in Excess' In letters to General Electric and United Technologies, Mr. Orr demanded that they refund to the Government a total of $208 million in profits that he said were ''significantly in excess of those negotiated by the Government.''
