aVCompensation continues to swell for top corporate management even as wages for the work force rise only marginally, a wage gap that some people consider a problem for the economy and society. The most recent of Business Week's annual studies found that at the 365 biggest companies in the country, the ratio of the chief executive's pay to that of a factory worker grew to 326 to 1 in 1997. The ratio was 44 to 1 in 1965. High time then, according to an advocacy group in Boston called United for a Fair Economy, to bring the issue to the board room. This year, the group's Responsible Wealth project has recruited shareholders to file resolutions at eight companies to examine the wage gaps within their labor forces.
