aVThe GE Capital Corporation, the financial arm of the General Electric Company, said yesterday that it would buy the Leucadia National Corporation's Colonial Penn automobile insurance unit for $950 million. Colonial Penn, which has $515 million in annual premiums, insures low-risk drivers who are, on average, 50 years old. It uses direct marketing to sell to them. For Leucadia, an investment company with businesses ranging from manufacturing to banking, the agreement is another step in its effort to divest itself of its insurance holdings. The company said in April that it would sell the Colonial Penn Life Insurance Company and the Providential Life Insurance Company to Conseco Inc. for $460 million. The $1.41 billion Leucadia that will reap on the combined sales is more than 10 times the $130 million it paid the Florida Power and Light Company for the insurance businesses in 1991.
