VThe staff of the Oregon Public Utility Commission will recommend that the planned purchase of the Portland General Corporation by the Enron Corporation be blocked, Portland General said today. The utility said that it had been told about the recommendation by a senior staff member. The staff's final report is due April 11, and members of the commission will then vote on whether to approve the transaction. Enron, a Houston-based energy company, said in July that it would buy Portland General, offering $2.13 billion in Enron stock and agreeing to assume $1.1 billion of the utility's debt. The staff found that Enron's offer of $61 million in cost savings and rate reductions did not offer sufficient benefits to meet the statutory burden needed to approve the transaction, Portland General said. The acquisition must also be approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
p1975
aVJohn F. Welch Jr., the chairman and chief executive of the General Electric Company, was paid $6.3 million in salary and bonus last year, an 18.4 percent increase over his 1995 cash compensation of $5.32 million, a company proxy statement disclosed yesterday. Mr. Welch's total compensation last year, including 320,000 stock options, was $30.01 million, a one-third increase from the $22.5 million he earned in 1995, according to calculations by Graef S. Crystal, an executive compensation expert and critic of outsized paychecks for chief executives of publicly traded companies.
