p1990
aVIn an effort to introduce more competition into Pentagon procurement, the Navy has proposed that the General Electric Company be required to share with its chief rival, Pratt & Whitney, the technology for an aircraft engine that the Navy expects to buy for the next 20 years, according to an internal memorandum. The proposal, made by Navy Secretary John F. Lehman Jr., is part of a continuing Defense Department effort to save money by moving away from single suppliers. A spokesman for General Electric said in a telephone interview from Lynn, Mass., today that his company had been informed of the Navy proposal but had not yet agreed to it. It is not clear, the spokesman added, whether the Navy could legally force his company to share the technology for the F-404 engine. Until now G.E. has faced no competition in the sale of the F-404 to the Navy.
