aVThe New England Power Company burns a lot of coal at its waterfront power plant here: 2,400 tons a day, day in, day out, year round. Because about 10 percent of coal is unburnable sand and shale -- what one executive calls "prehistoric dirt" -- the result is about 300,000 tons of coal ash a year that must somehow be removed. That is a quarter of a ton of ash a year for each residential electricity customer.
