VKATRINA INSURANCE RULING A federal judge in Mississippi sided with home insurance companies and ruled that they do not have to pay for the flooding that destroyed tens of thousands of homes in Hurricane Katrina. [C1.] STOCKS RISE ON PRICE DATA Wall Street rallied after a government report showing inflation softening at the wholesale level encouraged hopes among investors that the Federal Reserve may be able to avoid further interest rate increases. [C1.] THE SCIENCE OF BATTERIES In trying to improve the endurance of batteries, scientists cannot overcome some basic hurdles of chemistry and physics. The more energy that is stored in a smaller package, the more volatile and dangerous that package becomes. The volatility of some batteries became clear with Dell's recall of 4.1 million laptop batteries. Dell said the batteries, made by Sony, could catch fire. [C1.] BAE'S GROWTH PLANS BAE, the British military contractor, says it is neither British nor American, but a new breed of military contractor -- a trans-Atlantic supplier. The chief executive has even hinted he might move the company to the United States if he gets more Pentagon business, a goal that is central to his strategy for growth. [C1.] AIR DELAYS CONTINUE Passengers flying out of Heathrow Airport in London endured a sixth day of disruption as airlines weighed the possibility of seeking compensation from the airport operator and the British government, in an attempt to avoid passing costs on to customers. [C8.] AIRPORT OPERATOR CRITICIZED BAA, the British airport operator, faced continued criticism for its handling of new security procedures, with passengers and airline executives asking why the company did not hire temporary workers to meet the demand for security checks. [C8.] MEDICARE DRUG PREMIUMS Federal officials announced that the average premium for Medicare prescription drug coverage next year would be about $24 a month, which is the same as this year and 40 percent less than originally estimated for 2007. [A12.] TRADE WITH VENEZUELA Even as the talk from Caracas and Washington grows more hostile and the countries seem to be growing ever farther apart, trade between Venezuela and the United States has reached its highest level ever. [A3.] MONSANTO MAKES ACQUISITION Monsanto will acquire the Delta and Pine Land Company, the nation's leading supplier of cotton seeds, in a move that will add to Monsanto's commanding position in the business of biotechnology crops. [C4.] UNAPPROVED PLANT FOUND An unapproved type of genetically engineered grass has been found in the wild in what scientists say could be the first instance in America in which a biotechnology plant has established itself outside a farm. [A13.] JOCKEYING FOR NICKEL MINER The three-way scramble continued among companies trying to acquire Inco, the nickel miner based in Toronto. [C8.] WAL-MART EARNINGS FALL Wal-Mart Stores reported its first decline in quarterly income in 10 years, blaming the financial slip on troubles in foreign markets. [C3.] CHANGES AT PFIZER Less than three weeks after being named Pfizer's chief executive, Jeffrey B. Kindler moved to put his stamp on the drug maker with a wide-ranging executive reorganization. [C3.] EX-CHIEF DECLARED A FUGITIVE The hunt for Jacob Alexander, former chief executive of Comverse, was stepped up after the Federal Bureau of Investigation declared him a fugitive and said agents were seeking his arrest. Mr. Alexander was charged last week with conspiracy to commit securities fraud. [C3.] MAKING THE CASE FOR G.E. Late last month, an array of General Electric executives stood before about 100 analysts and attempted to prove that all of G.E.'s wildly disparate units march to the same tune. In a sense, G.E. was preaching to the choir, with most analysts covering G.E. rating its shares a buy. But investors are not heeding the advice. For more than a year, analysts have predicted that the stock would reach $40 or more. Instead, it has hovered around the mid-30's. [C5.] FOOD SITE WITH ATTITUDE Chow.com, a new food Web site, hopes to inject a hip sensibility into its smorgasbord of recipes, restaurant reviews, party hints, video tutorials and coverage of the marketing and culture of food. All this is aimed at a younger audience than the major food Web sites tend to attract. [F1.] GOOGLE'S WIRELESS PLANS Even as it rolls out a local wireless Internet service in the city where it is based, Google says it has no plans to position itself as a national provider of such services. [C7.] ONLINE ONLINE: DEALBOOK A report on mergers and acquisitions, up-to-the-minute news on Wall Street and a look at the behind-the-scenes maneuvering is at nytimes.com/dealbook. Business Briefing An article on these developments is at nytimes.com/business. STAPLES, THE OFFICE SUPPLIES RETAILER, said that its profit rose 19 percent in the second quarter, driven by market share gains in North America and strong back-to-school sales. Staples said its income rose to $161.2 million, from $135.2 million, a year earlier. Sales rose 12 percent, to $3.88 billion from $3.47 billion. (REUTERS)
