aVLast week, Travers J. Bell Jr., chairman and founder of the only black-owned New York Stock Exchange member firm, lost in his attempt to take control of the Freedom National Bank, the only black-owned commercial bank in New York. Mr. Bell, who is 42 years old, vows to continue the battle, but even if he fails, Mr. Bell is building a growing financial empire that stretches from Brooklyn to Africa. Back in 1971, Mr. Bell formed Daniels & Bell Inc. with $175,000 in capital. (Willie E. Daniels, the firm's co-founder left the company several years ago to go into the restaurant business.) Daniels & Bell now has about $2 million in capital and will earn in excess of $2 million in the fiscal year ending April 30, according to Mr. Bell. With 15 employees - including three floor traders - Mr. Bell claims 300 retail clients and an equal number of institutional clients, among them Exxon, Chase Manhattan, General Electric and Levi Strauss. And, the firm has created a niche for itself by underwriting securities of emerging minority businesses and participating in large distribution syndicates formed by other investment banks.
