aVWHEN Morgan Stanley & Company, the most prestigious of investment banks, looks to its roots, it sees the industrial financier J. Pierpont Morgan, whose own American ancestry dates to 1636. An offspring of the House of Morgan, Morgan Stanley has grown rich as the banker to blue chip corporate America, with a client list that is the envy of Wall Street. It earns a 20 percent after-tax return on equity. Each year, it either leads or is in the top tier of the numerous lists that rank Wall Street firms. In 1981, it appeared as lead manager on $11.76 billion worth of corporate stock and bond issues, taking the No. 1 slot by that measure for the third consecutive year. Its clients, including 15 to 20 of the nation's 50 largest companies, carry names like American Telephone, General Electric, Exxon and Du Pont. But the world of Wall Street is changing, in ways that could threaten to crack Morgan's noble walls. New regulations, primarily the Securities and Exchange Commission's Rule 415, which allows corporations to sell securities directly to investors, pose a threat. Upstart competitors are hunting among Morgan's clients; Morgan has even bent its rule on being sole manager of corporate industrial issues. A retail distribution network, which Morgan lacks, is considered by many the key to growth.
