NaVT HE restructuring of the American Telephone and Telegraph Company will require certain dramatic changes in the direction, style and business philosophy of all of A.T.& T.'s subsidiaries. But of all Ma Bell's children, probably none faces more of a transformation - and risks and opportunities - than Western Electric. For more than 100 years, Western's ''sole mission in life,'' in its own words, has been to manufacture or buy almost all of the telecommunications equipment used by the 22 local Bell operating subsidiaries - everything from the paper clips for their offices to the software for their computers. But the settlement announced Jan. 8 of the Justice Department's seven-year-old antitrust suit against A.T.& T. means that Western, itself an industrial colossus as big as the United States Steel Company, must remold itself. A.T.& T. will have to shed its 22 local telephone company subsidiaries, with whom Western did the lion's share of its business. The settlement permits A.T.& T. to retain Western, the Bell Telephone Laboratories, which provide the innovations for most of Western's products, and its Long Lines long-distance network. In return for the divestiture, the Government not only a greed to drop the suit against A.T.& T., but also to eliminate all restrictions upon its entry into the computer-telecommunications field.
