aVBONN THE collapse of AEG-Telefunken under a $3.5 billion mountain of debt, however shocking, seemed almost inevitable. The giant electrical products company - second-largest in West Germany after Siemens -had been rocked by debt, competition and mismanagement since the mid-1970's. But the company's decision to enter composition proceedings - Germa@ny's equivalent to America's Chapter 11 court protection from creditors - reflected more than its own internal errors. The failure of AEG has also disclosed a sense of fragility beneath this country's image as a powerful, resilient economic force. Germany's strength in electrical technology, the backbone of AEG's business, helped propel the country to economic prominence in the past. AEG somehow symbolized the resourceful and resilient aspect of Germany's economy. Rebounding from the devastation of World War II, which eliminated more than 90 percent of its plants, AEG rose to become Germany's 15th-largest corporation.
p2220
aVFOR executives in the machine tool industry, which makes all the t ools that either cut or form metal, the past two years have been a l ittle like watching sand run through an hour glass. Machine tools a re being made and shipped out, but new orders are scarce and the b acklog of orders is getting perilously low. In addition, competitionf rom the Japanese is mounting and some machine tool plants are a ntiquated and in need of new capital. In this environment, the Acme-Cleveland Corporation, the eighthlargest machine tool company and one that generally underperforms the industry, was expected to fare worse than most companies. Instead, it is holding its own. Moreover, changes in the company's cost structure are being dealt with so quickly that analysts now say Acme-Cleveland could outperform some other companies when orders begin to return. But despite its best efforts, Acme-Cleveland faces problems. Like other companies in the industry, it has had to deal with a sharp drop in shipments. Orders have fallen 75 percent industrywide since 1980's first quarter and there is no sign of an upturn.
p2221
aVATLANTIQUE, the diversified French engineering group that builds everything from pasta factories to the world's fastest train, is at the center of efforts to frustrate President Reagan's attempt to halt construction of a new Soviet pipeline. In defiance of an American ban, the French Government has ordered Alsthom-Atlantique to supply the huge rotors, which it makes under license from General Electric, for turbine-powered compressor plants that will send Siberian natural gas through a 3,700-mile pipeline into Western European factories and homes. Without these large compressors, the project as originally planned would be doomed. The spoiler role is one that Alsthom-Atlantique, the only European company with the technology to build the rotors, would rather not play. ''Of course we have to do what the Government decides, but we don't want a row with the Americans,'' said Roger Chalvon-Demersay, a senior Alsthom-Atlantique executive, stressing that the company has worked closely with General Electric since the end of World War II. And there were rumors in Paris that the company had fought behind the scenes to delay the French Government's order while European governments continued diplomatic efforts to bring about a White House change of heart.
