aVIT began nine years ago with a sheet of ledger paper containing 30 or so names culled from a roster of the nation's 500 largest industrial companies. Harry J. Gray's hit list, as it came to be known, has been revised many times. At one point, it vanished in the theft of a car belonging to the executive in whose briefcase it was entrusted for maximum security. But by then the names had been committed to memory by Mr. Gray, the chairman, president and chief executive officer of the United Technologies Corporation, and the lieutenants charged with implementing his 1973 blueprint for transforming a Connecticut-based aerospace company into a worldscale technological giant. The Otis Elevator Company was one name on the list, the Carrier Corporation another, the Bendix Corporation a third. In 1976, after its management put up fierce resistance to his wooing, Otis was assimilated into United Technologies. In 1979, following an even more bitter battle in which the citizens of Syracuse, N.Y., united to try to thwart the Hartford raider, Carrier disappeared into the United Technologies fold.
