aNaVIn a year at the helm of the Consumers Power Company, William T. McCormick Jr. has generally won praise for steering the nation's 14th-largest utility away from financial disaster. But many skeptics contend that a vital element of the company's turnaround may yet elude him. The root of the problems confronting the 41-year-old chairman and chief executive is Consumers' 18-year, $4.2 billion attempt to construct a nuclear power plant in Midland, Mich. In 1984, when Consumers abandoned the installation, then 85 percent complete, the utility was saddled with debt and losses, and the Michigan Public Service Commission forced it to cancel dividends on its common stock until 1988. Now Mr. McCormick's hope is that the cause of Consumers' downfall can be used to insure its comeback. His goal is to convince the Public Service Commission to approve rate increases so the company can recoup, over 15 years, $2.1 billion of the $3.7 billion in Midland investment that is still on its books.
p2572
aNaVTHE news last July that France's leading telephone company was buying the ITT Corporation's telecommunications business made headlines in the United States and Europe. But few people read the reports as attentively as Karlheinz Kaske, chief executive of Siemens A.G., the giant West German electrical company. The deal posed a threat to Siemens, since the ITT package included Standard Elektrik Lorenz, a major Siemens competitor in German telecommunications. Worse still, it was taking place just as the American Telephone and Telegraph Company was angling to buy a share in France's second-largest telecommunications company - thus raising the prospect of two French-American telecommunications partnerships. Mr. Kaske responded with characteristic agility. In two frenetic weeks, he opened negotiations from Munich, made an offer of $47 million -roughly three times the American bid - for A.T.&T.'s French target, a stake in Compagnie Generale de Constructions Telephoniques, and flew to Bonn and Paris to urge a ''European solution.'' ''If the French buy Standard Elektrik, that's O.K.,'' Mr. Kaske said. ''We won't be provincial. The only thing we want is a similar opportunity in the French market.''
