aVSherlock Holmes sniffed out crime and corruption in London's East End. For Martin and Pearl Tytell, the quarry is the same, but the locale is the corporate suite. From fraud to poison pen letters -typed or handwritten - scriveners' dirty deeds are unravelled at the Tytell's Questioned Documents Labratory at 116 Fulton Street. It's all done in the interests of justice, not to mention the standard corporate fee of ''several thousand dollars'' a case; $750 a day for courtroom testimony.
p2676
aVIn the dark, wood-paneled partners' room of Morgan Grenfell & Company, it would seem that little has changed since the firm took over the gray stone headquarters in 1924. The six most senior directors, as they are now called, still labor together in the high-ceilinged hall, their chief executive at one end under a portrait of the patriarch, Junius Morgan. But although the late Mr. Morgan continues to keep a watchful eye over the investment banking firm's senior executives, Morgan Grenfell today is in fact quite different. Four months ago, the last substantial connection to the celebrated family was severed when the Morgan Guaranty Trust Company agreed to sell virtually all of its one-third interest in its London cousin to a group of British institutions for about $40 million. The transaction reflected the increased importance of the outward expansion of investment banking, and the growing competition in this ''internationalization,'' as the bankers describe the growing links among the world's major capital markets.
p2677
aVThe International Business Machines Corporation, the world's largest computer c ompany, is reported to be o n the verge of a major reorganization, spurred in part by heated com petition and internal conflicts within its sales groups. Executives of the company, which has its headquarters in Armonk, N.Y., were said by analysts and sources within I.B.M.'s globespanning organization to be explaining the shifts at meetings with division vice presidents yesterday. The changes apparently include scrapping its traditional divisionbased sales approach, in which separate sales representatives from the data processing, general systems and office products units might all call on the same customer. Instead, I.B.M. customers will be able to order a full range of I.B.M. products, ranging from its large mainframe computers, to small desktop business computers from the same sales personnel.
p2678
aVMICHAEL JONES had been a Bell telephone salesman for 10 years when the company told him last spring that he would have to prove himself again. Mr. Jones, who requested his real name not be used, was told to write a report and submit other documents showing that he knew how to organize an account, knew the Bell product line, knew the Bell marketing strategies. He was given less than a month to prepare the report, on his own time. A special board of crack salesmen was set up to judge his dossier and those of his co-workers. ''I feel like it was kind of crazy to all of a sudden turn around and justify your existence,'' Mr. Jones said, who left Bell in June and now works for another telecommunications company. The American Telephone and Telegraph Company does not think it crazy. It is requiring all 6,500 of its account executives to be certified, a test so rigorous that one of the executives in charge estimated that only 15 to 20 percent are passing on the first try.
p2679
aVAn intriguing thing happens when certain metals are cooled to extremely low temperatures. At about 415 degrees below zero Fahrenheit - close to what is called absolute zero because matter can get no colder - these metals lose all resistance to electricity. When electricity can move without resistance, a dramatic improvement in the efficiency of energy transmission is possible. So is the creation of supermagnets.
