VAfter taking lessons in Chinese cuisine, where she learned that good cooking is easier on a good stove, Beverly Savage, a reporter for the Newark Star Ledger and an avid amateur cook, went for broke. Remodeling her Hoboken kitchen, she bought a three-foot-wide, sixburner Garland range, a model more usually seen in a restaurant kitchen. ''If it's something you can afford, and you care about cooking,'' she said, ''it's worth it.'' The range, with a salamander broiler above and an oven below, which has circulating air for more even heat, cost her more than $1,200. Miss Savage is not alone by any means. In metropolitan areas around the country, commercial stoves are becoming a hot item in the home. In New York the Garland controls about 50 percent of the market for commercial ranges, according to the company, a subsidiary of the Welbilt Corporation of Maspeth, N.Y., which markets traditional home stoves under its own name.
