NaVThe General Electric Company said that it had reached a five-year agreement with Chloride Silent Power Ltd. of Britain for joint research and development of a battery for utility energy storage and to power vehicles. Elbert F. Lowell, general manager of G.E.'s Energy Systems Program Department, said the joint effort was being made to accelerate the development of a sodium-sulfur-based ''beta battery,'' which is expected to outperform conventional lead-acid batteries. The beta battery can store more than four times the energy of conventional batteries of equal weight and has a projected life of at least five years in vehicles and 10 years or more in utility applications, G.E. said.
