p2701
aVThe Supreme Court ruled today that Federal law allowed private pension plans to reduce a member's pension benefits by the amount of any compensation award received for a jobrelated disability. The 8-to-0 opinion was a setback for retired workers. It affirmed a decision by a Federal appeals court that rejected challenges to two private pension plans by employees whose workmen's compensation awards were deducted from their pensions under the terms of the pension plans of the General Motors Corporation and Raybestos-Manhattan Inc. Regulations issued by the Treasury Department provide that such ''offsets'' are permitted by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, which covered both pension plans. However, a New Jersey state law, enacted in 1977, prohibits the offsets. The plaintiffs worked at New Jersey plants of the two companies.
p2702
aVThe Envirotech Corporation, a pollution control equipment manufacturer that grew rich on the environmental fervor of the 1970's, finds itself facing a huge debt, slow sales and heavy losses. The Menlo Park, Calif., company has moved to disengage itself from operations in air pollution control products, but it says that it still has the largest line of waste water equipment in the country. Envirotech, blaming the Federal Environmental Protection Agency for a large share of its problems, has said that it is now focusing its operations on the production of equipment for mining and other industrial processes. The company asserts that the E.P.A. is taking steps to make changes in its procedures, as it was asked to do by Envirotech and several other leading companies in the industry.
