aVIN April 1974, directors of the Consolidated Edison Company of New York made a decision that had a devastating impact on their company's stock and simultaneously sent shock waves rippling through shares of other electric utilities. For the first time since 1885, Consolidated Edison omitted its quarterly dividend. Earlier that year, shares of Con Edison had traded as high as 21 1/2. By the end of 1974, in the throes of a bear market, the stock sank as low as 6.
