aVThe General Electric Company said yesterday that it would manufacture and sell an industrial robot developed by an Italian company as part of its strategy to become a major supplier of equipment for factory automation. The G.E. announcement said that a new group had been formed to develop and market robots and that the initial entry into the robot business would be followed by additional robots. G.E. will either design these itself or license them from others. General Electric said its agreement, with DEA of Italy, gives it nonexclusive rights to manufacture and sell worldwide a DEA robot that can assemble small items such as automobile parts. In North America, G.E. has exclusive rights to the product unless DEA wants to sell its robots on its own, according to Julius A. Mirabal, general manager of G.E.'s new robot group.
