NaVThe president of the Ford Motor Company thought he had a development important enough to call a news conference. The company's researchers, he announced, had achieved a breakthrough in advanced battery technology that would make mass production of electric cars feasible within five to 10 years. That was in 1966. The first car has yet to appear in a dealer's showroom and Ford officials say the sodium sulfur battery that Arjay Miller hailed so proudly 15 years ago is still stalled in the laboratory. Ford's false start is a typical episode in the faltering development of electrically powered cars. Once viewed as a means of weaning the country from expensive, undependable oil imports, the outlook for electric cars has become uncertain. Many auto executives and industry analysts doubt there will be significant numbers of electric cars on the highways before the end of the decade, if largescale production begins at all.
p2721
aVThe General Electric Company reported yesterday that its secondquarter earnings rose 8.2 percent from the similar period a year ago on a 12.1 percent gain in revenue. Earnings in the quarter were $436 million, or $1.92 a share, compared with $403 million, or $1.77 a share, in the second quarter of 1980. Sales rose to $6.95 billion from $6.2 billion.
p2722
aVI T has become fashionable, with the arrival of the Reagan Administration, to lament the ''undue burdens'' of regulation in our society. This trend is now rearing its head in the electric utility industry. Electric company officials, frustrated with what they consider the laggardly pace and niggardly size of rate relief from the state public utility commissions, are starting to discuss the advisability of deregulating the construction and financing of power plants. Their basic proposal: Let electric companies continue to be regulated at the retail level by the state commissions. However, allow freedom of entry in the capital-intensive generating end of the business and end price regulation. Anyone who can build a power plant would then have the right to sell electricity in the marketplace of retail electric companies. Since the return on investment on such facilities would be unregulated, a large number of companies could be expected to seek to enter the wholesale market, ensuring competition and reasonable prices of power.
p2723
aVCanada and the United States, which have two of the world's most closely connected economies, are being drawn even closer together in the energy field these days by rapidly growing new links in electricity. Vast amounts of electrical energy, most of it heading south, are flowing on new transmission lines across the 3,986.8-mile-long border between the two countries. Some experts predict that the two-way trade in this energy will exceed $10 billion by the end of the decade, compared with less than $800 million now. ''The idea has been around a long time,'' said one American diplomat, ''but the interest is suddenly growing now. It's really astounding.''
p2724
