aVThe pent-up demand for long-term financing among large corporations was demonstrated yesterday when the International Business Machines Corporation and the General Foods Corporation announced plans for a total of $600 million of new issues. The quick actions to arrange borrowings came with bond market yields declining for six weeks and investment bankers discerning continuing investor demand for new high-yielding issues. The yield for bellwether 30-year Treasury issues has fallen from more than 14.25 percent in early May to about 12.6 percent now. Despite the decline, yields are still high enough that investors are buying heavily and may absorb more than $5 billion of new issues this month.
p2735
aVAn intense debate - partly philosophical, partly practical, entirely political - is under way in Washington about the role and future of the Export-Import Bank, the 47-year-old institution that provides low-interest loans to finance the sale of American products abroad. The outcome of the debate could set the tone for the Reagan Administration's evolving export policy and could significantly influence the prospects for narrowing the nation's trade deficit, which is now running at about $30 billion a year. The philosophical debate on the role of the bank pits the conservative theorists and budget-cutters of the Administration, who have proposed slashing the bank's lending authority, against an ad hoc coalition of business, labor and the bank's Congressional backers, who want to expand its lending authority to aid exports. The struggle has reached a peak just as the bank is about to report its first losing quarter in history and when the latest Government projections indicate that it may run out of money within four years. The loss, expected to be about $30 million, will be for the fourth fiscal quarter of 1981, ending Sept. 30.
