aVThe house that Darryl F. Zanuck built contains far more riches than meet the casual eye. The rabid interest among a band of corporate suitors of the 20th Century-Fox Film Corporation stretches beyond a simple desire to be part of the glitter and glamour of making movies. Tucked within the framework of the big film company is a bevy of lucrative assets, including some of the choicest real estate in the world, most of which is carried on the Fox books at well below what the assets might fetch in today's marketplace. It comes as little surprise, then, that Marvin Davis, a Denver oil millionaire, has offered close to $700 million to buy Fox. ''If you took all the assets of this company and sold them off piecemeal,'' says Anthony Hoffman, a securities analyst at A.G. Becker, ''you'd probably get a good deal more money than Mr. Davis is preparing to pay.''
