aVWorkers at the General Dynamics Corporation here have accused some managers at the company of falsifying time cards, and say the practice has led to overbilling on Government contracts. Although the giant military contractor is currently under indictment for fraud, the charges against it have not included instances of incorrect billing for employee time. But at least one other major military contractor, the General Electric Company, has faced such charges, and was temporarily barred from Pentagon work in early 1985. G.E. pleaded guilty to 108 counts of falsifying time cards, and was fined $1.04 million, the maximum allowable. G.E. was also ordered to pay back the $800,000 that was falsely billed. In scores of interviews outside factory gates, inside their homes and over the telephone since last Friday, many General Dynamics workers said that supervisors at the General Dynamics plants here sometimes incorrectly billed employee hours to the Federal Government. The workers also said that, until recently, managers in some departments filled out time cards after the workers signed them. The employees in those departments signed the cards at the beginning of each week and never saw them again, they said.
