aVOn Jan. 23, Ralph D. DeNunzio was presiding over the regular biweekly meeting of the management committee of Kidder, Peabody & Company when his secretary broke in to deliver a note. Mr. DeNunzio, Kidder's rotund, 55-year-old chief executive, had just received word that Morgan Stanley & Company, for five decades the model of an elite private Wall Street investment bank, had decided to sell shares to the public. That message became a catalyst, setting off a process that ended just three months later with 80 percent of the 121-year-old Kidder being swallowed by the highly regarded financial services unit of the General Electric Company for a whopping $600 million. Kidder's hard-driving professionals, a number of whom recounted the events leading to the acquisition in interviews last week, had read the message about Morgan Stanley in one way: Kidder had to act, and act fast. 'The Capital Question' ''I knew exactly what the note was,'' said Max C. Chapman, the obsessively competitive ex-Marine who heads Kidder's fixed-income department and sits on its management committee. ''I felt like we were falling further and further behind. We told Ralph that we just had to address the capital question.''
