p2855
aVFOR several years, industrial and commercial concerns around the country have been cutting millions of dollars from their utility bills by producing their own electric and thermal energy, using power plants that harness waste heat that would otherwise escape into the air. Such cogeneration systems recycle waste heat to make steam - used in industrial processes - or for heating. There are several kinds of cogeneration systems in use, but recently a steam-injected gas turbine, or STIG, process has been gaining in popularity. According to a study at Princeton University's Center for Energy and Environmental Studies, STIG systems generate more power than other cogeneration approaches, but use the same amount of fuel. Eric D. Larson and Robert H. Williams, research scientists who conducted the Princeton study, said that a STIG plant could produce as much as six megawatts of power, compared with three and a half megawatts for a standard gas turbine plant using the same amount of fuel. Six megawatts is enough power to meet the needs of 5,000 homes.
