aNaVThree of America's biggest names in electronics and photography are joining with Japanese manufacturers in an effort to take over the home movie market. Over the last two days, all three announced that they would offer their versions of a new generation of small, lightweight videotape cameras. For consumers, the appeal is that for an initial investment of $1,000 to $2,000, which is much less than most of the heavier, bulkier videotape cameras now sell for, they can see the fruits of their amateur photography instantly on their television screen. For the American companies - Kodak, RCA and General Electric - the new cameras represent a campaign to combine their own well- known labels with Japan's manufacturing cost advantage to crack what many believe could be a huge United States market for video cameras, an outgrowth of the video cassette recorders that are now in one out of 10 American homes.
