aVThe Navy is expected to announce shortly that it will turn to General Electric for a jet engine for an advanced version of its F-14 fighter, a plane that until now has been powered by an engine built by the Pratt & Whitney Aircraft Group of the United Technologies Corporation. The Navy decision would be another blow to Pratt & Whitney, a major employer in Connecticut, which only last week saw the Air Force decide to give a major share of its tactical fighter jet engine production to General Electric. A source at the Naval Air Systems Command said today, ''There will be a change in manufacturer.'' But the terms of any new contract - for example, whether it would cover existing planes or new production - were unknown.
