aVOn the eve of the Air Force's recent announcement of the winner of its ''great engine war,'' Brian H. Rowe, the head of General Electric's engine group, was too nervous to sleep. After tossing about for hours in his bed in his hotel room in New York, he got up and watched a series of reruns on early morning TV. It was to be a long day. Following a morning news conference in New York where he announced a new commercial aviation venture with Rolls-Royce, Mr. Rowe, a senior vice president at G.E., flew back by jet to this Cincinnati suburb to await word of the Air Force's $12 billion decision. There were plenty of rumors and they told of a big victory for General Electric. But there was nothing firm until early afternoon. Finally, an Ohio Congressman called with the word that G.E. had captured 75 percent of the orders.
p2885
aVAmid persistent speculation that the Air Force has decided to award up to 70 percent of a multibillion-dollar jet-engine order to the General Electric Company, Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger said today that the contract would be awarded in ''the next few days'' In testimony today to the House Armed Services Committee, Mr. Weinberger stressed that ''no final decision has been made'' on the massive contract. But, he said in response to a question, ''the award will be made in the next few days and, when it is, the benefits of the competition will be obvious,'' The Defense Department often announces such large contracts at 4 P.M. on Fridays in order to avoid influencing the stock market. The contract, worth an estimated $10 billion to $14 billion, has pitted G.E. against the Pratt & Whitney Aircraft Division of the United Technologies Corporation for the rights to build some 2,400 engines for the Air Force's F-15 and F-16 fighters. Because of the high stakes and political considerations involved in the huge contract, it has long been assumed in Congressional and industry circles that the Air Force would divide the award between the two companies in some fashion.
