(lp2923
VAs one of the biggest purveyors of financing for leveraged buyouts and an aggressive proponent of ''creative financing'' for American companies, the General Electric Credit Corporation is growing rapidly in the turbulent financial services industry. The credit subsidiary of the General Electric Company has been expanding on its business beyond consumer financing for more than 20 years. Beginning in 1965, long before leveraged buyouts became a fad on Wall Street, the company began financing such transactions, and has been active in more than five such transactions each year. The company has, nonetheless, remained outside the increasing controversy that has surrounded L.B.O's in recent months by adhering to a long- standing policy of financing the buyouts of relatively small companies in transactions negotiated in relatively friendly terms. For example, two groups that have received G.E. credit financing for these transactions in the last 12 months included the senior management of Microdot Inc., a subsidiary of Northwest Industries, which was taken private for $125 million, and Farley Industries, which bought out the shares of the N.L. Metal Products Group for $118 million, Some Warnings Sounded Leveraged buyouts are transactions in which public companies are taken private by management or others who borrow to purchase the shares. As a lender, G.E. Credit has typically assumed that future earnings of the companies would be used to pay off the buyout debt.
