aVIn Michigan, a major utility is warning its opponents that, if they do not drop their opposition to its nuclear plants, it will declare bankruptcy. In New York, Governor Cuomo is threatening to let the Long Island Lighting Company go bankrupt if it refuses to cancel its reactor. Around the country, at least four large utilities with giant nuclear projects that have soured may soon face bankruptcy, an event unknown for utilities for 40 years. Bankruptcy would cause traumatic disruptions for company executives, regulators, creditors, stockholders and bankers, and it would probably mean higher rates for customers, the experts say, but they see little reduction in the reliability of service. But according to experts in bankruptcy law and in utility regulation, operation of a utility might be considerably easier after a bankruptcy filing than before, especially regarding such critical needs as the ability to borrow money.
