aV-1970's, allegations of fraud on nuclear submarine contracts at the General Dynamics Corporation's Electric Boat division have acted like a sore that refuses to heal. Despite several lengthy Federal investigations that ended without prosecution, new queries by Congress and the Justice Department now threaten to tear the wound open again. Dozens of internal General Dynamics documents recently released by Senator William Proxmire have added fuel to charges made by P. Takis Veliotis, the shipyard's former chief executive who was indicted last year on kickback charges and is now a fugitive in Greece. He has told Government investigators that poor performance at Electric Boat contributed to huge claims against the Navy, that General Dynamics ''bought in'' to the submarine program by submitting unrealistically low bids, and that it threatened to close the shipyard to scare the Navy into settling the claims. His accusations are still being investigated. What is clear, however, is that there will be increasingly intense scrutiny of the country's largest military contractor - and particularly its ties to the Navy. In addition to Mr. Proxmire's initiative, the House Energy and Commerce Committee's oversight panel has sent auditors to General Dynamics' offices in Groton, Conn., where Electric Boat is based, as well as to St. Louis, and Washington to examine company records for questionable gift-giving and entertainment expenses.
