aVCHARGES IN HEWLETT CASE -- Patricia C. Dunn, the former chairwoman of Hewlett-Packard, and four other people were charged with felonies for illegally obtaining private phone records of company directors, journalists and others. [Page A1.] WHEN LEAK QUERIES STARTED -- The former Hewlett-Packard chief executive Carleton S. Fiorina ordered the first of a series of leak investigations into contacts by board members with journalists in January 2005, according to her memoir, ''Tough Choices'', which is scheduled to be published on Monday. [C1.] OPTIONS BACKDATING AT APPLE -- Apple Computer said an internal review of its stock option practices found that Steven P. Jobs, the chief executive, knew that the company was backdating options to increase their value. [C1.] G.M. MERGER TALKS END -- General Motors called off its talks for an alliance with Nissan and Renault after the Japanese and French companies refused to pay billions of dollars to cement the deal. [C1.] 'CORRECTION' IN HOUSING -- The Federal Reserve chairman, Ben S. Bernanke, left, said the United States housing market was in a ''substantial correction'' that would lop about a percentage point off economic growth in the second half and would restrain the expansion next year. ''There is currently a substantial correction going on in the housing market,'' Mr. Bernanke said. The decline in residential housing construction is one of the ''major drags that is causing the economy to slow.'' [C11.] SURVIVING A SIDE-IMPACT CRASH -- A driver's risk of being killed in a side-impact crash decreases by more than a third if the vehicle has head-protecting side-curtain air bags, according to a study of accident data by the Insurance Institute for Highway. [C13.] SHARES RALLY FOR ANOTHER RECORD -- Shares rallied the most in seven weeks, as the Standard & Poor's 500-stock index set a five-year high and the Dow Jones industrial average climbed above 11,800 for the first time. Nasdaq shares rose more than 2 percent, their highest level in five months. [C15.] SIGNS OF SLUGGISH ECONOMY -- In further signs of a sluggish economy, orders to factories for manufactured goods were weak for a second month and activity in service industries was the slowest in more than three years. [C11.] PROBLEMS FOR HEDGE FUNDS -- Hedge funds -- investments for institutions like pension funds and endowments and the wealthy -- have hit a rough patch. Returns for many hedge funds, which are supposed to be the market beaters, have paled in comparison to stocks. And yet investors have hardly blinked. Eager for the rich, if not always predictable, returns that hedge funds promise, they continue to pour money into them and hope the next fund with a big problem will not be one of theirs. [C1.] NEW TACTICS IN THE KPMG CASE -- Prosecutors shifted tactics in the KPMG tax shelter case, taking steps to try 18 defendants in two separate groups, one of former partners and executives and one of more junior employees. [C11.] VW BUYS TRUCK STAKE -- The German automaker Volkswagen said it had bought a 15 percent stake in the Austrian truck maker MAN, part of an effort to build a three-way alliance with MAN, Scania of Sweden and its own truck business. Earlier this month, MAN, which is based in Munich, made a $12.2 billion hostile bid for Scania, in which Volkswagen already owns an 18.7 percent stake. Scania's management and Volkswagen rejected that bid. [C13.] WAL-MART DROPS ESTIMATE -- Wal-Mart Stores unexpectedly lowered its estimate for monthly growth in sales at stores open at least a year after discovering mistakes in calculations. [C3.] ICAHN OPPOSED IMCLONE DEAL -- ImClone Systems accused the billionaire investor Carl C. Icahn of sabotaging a proposal from a big drug maker to acquire it, but Mr. Icahn said he had opposed the deal because the offering price was too low. [C5.] PUBLIC SCHOOLS, PRIVATE MANAGEMENT -- In what would be the biggest change yet to the way New York City's school system is administered, officials are considering plans to hire private groups to manage scores of public schools at taxpayer expense. [A1.] OUTSOURCING SECURITY BREACHES -- India's outsourcing industry with its expanding base of American and European customers, has suffered a series of security breaches, tarnishing its reputation. [C15.] ONLINE DEALBOOK -- A report on mergers and acquisitions, up-to-the-minute news on Wall Street and a look at the behind-the-scenes maneuvering is at nytimes.com/dealbook. Business Briefing Articles on these developments are at nytimes.com/business. SHARES OF STARBUCKS soared yesterday, even before the company announced that its September sales growth figures trounced Wall Street estimates and that it had opened more than 2,000 new stores in its latest fiscal year. (AP) THE SHAW GROUP, a provider of engineering and construction services for the energy, chemical and construction industries, announced plans to pay $1.08 billion for a 20 percent stake in the group acquiring Westinghouse Electric. (AP)
