aVFrom the window of William A. Kistler Jr.'s 65th-floor office here, there are few apparent signs of trouble in the local economy. From this height, new office construction seems to spring up from a flat urban landscape like derricks in a rich Texas oilfield. But the view of prosperity below masks the growing problems in an industry whose wealth shaped this city. Mr. Kistler is president of the Hughes Tool Company, the world's largest manufacturer of drill bits for oil wells. For Hughes, and for most of the oil industry, 1982 has brought radical, sometimes devastating changes.
