aVAMID considerable publicity, the Carolina Power nad Light Company took a billion-dollar plunge into nuclear power in the early 1970's. Nuclear themes graced the cover of its annual reports and shareholders were told of fast rising nuclear output. In 1973, the company predicted that nearly two-thirds of its power would come from nuclear energy by 1982. But more recent annual reports have been less rosy - and 1982's will likely reflect a slowing in revenue and earnings growth - due to a performance slide in nuclear power generation. The slide has been caused by a series of major shutdowns that are forcing Carolina Power to spend more than $300 million to revamp its often sidelined plants. The once bright nuclear future has been delayed, not only for Carolina Power, but for a growing list of utilities across the nation that have been stung by big nuclear repair bills. Companies such as Florida Power and Light, New York's Consolidated Edison, Rochester Gas and Electric and Pittsburgh's Duquesne Light have, or will, spend hundreds of millions of dollars to rejuvenate plants, and to replace lost nuclear production with more costly coal or oil-fired power while repairs were being made.
