aVThe Big Three United States auto makers said they had formed a joint effort to share the costs of developing batteries for electric vehicles. The Ford Motor Company, the General Motors Corporation and the Chrysler Corporation said they had pledged $35 million to the project. They said they want to raise $100 million annually by 1993 from the Government and electric utilities to support advanced battery research. The venture, called the United States Advanced Battery Consortium, plans to contract with battery manufacturers and other organizations to conduct research on advanced battery technology. The consortium, which had been expected, reflects a growing push by local governments in the country's most polluted areas to require "ultra-clean" cars by the end of the century. Before auto makers can manufacture and market electric cars, however, they need batteries with enough power to accelerate vehicles to highway speeds and with enough storage capacity to keep vehicles running for 100 miles or more. John R. Wallace, director of Ford's electric vehicle programs, said the venture was inspired partly by a race with the Japanese.
