aVThe General Electric Company said it would cut up to 1,000 jobs, or 6 percent of the work force, at its Evendale, Ohio, plant because it lost the competition to build engines for the next generation of Air Force fighter planes. On Tuesday the Pentagon chose Pratt & Whitney, a division of the United Technologies Corporation, over G.E. to build engines for the Advanced Tactical Fighter. A team headed by the Lockheed Corporation won the contract, which could be worth $60 billion, to build nearly 650 of the radar-evading jets. "The A.T.F. was a big disappointment," said Rick Kennedy, a spokesman at the Evendale plant. "It will affect our business in terms of income and in terms of jobs." G.E. built $3 billion worth of engines for the military last year but expects that to drop to about $2.5 billion by 1992.
