aVIN 1978, the Conair Corporation lost Wall Street support as sales of hand-held blow dryers slowed. At the time, Conair held 25 percent of that market and its shares had done well on the company's soaring profits. But Conair's earnings plunged to 2 cents a share in the first quarter of 1978 from 29 cents in 1977's first quarter. Short sellers rejoiced, believing that a youthful growth stock was showing signs of middle age as its principal market approached maturity. The short sellers sell borrowed shares, hoping to replace them at lower cost as holders become disenchanted with a company's prospects.
