p3923
aVThe acid-rain controversy may provide a much-needed boost for the nation's depressed air-pollution control industry. If the present momentum in Congress is maintained, companies such as Combustion Engineering, General Electric, Babcock & Wilcox and Research-Cottrell could wind up competing for $5 billion or more in new business. Acid rain, which is causing widespread ecological damage, primarily in the northeastern United States and Canada, is largely the result of airborne sulfur dioxide that comes mainly from coal-burning power plants in the Middle West and the East. These emissions travel and change chemically in the atmosphere, ultimately increasing the acidity of precipitation over wide areas and provoking serious disruptions of plant and animal life. The Canadians argue that much of their acid rain is the result of pollution that drifts across the border. They are therefore trying to get the United States Environmental Protection Agency and Congress to put tough controls on sulfur emissions in this country.
p3924
aVHammacher Schlemmer, Manhattan's renowned purveyor of bizarre gadgetry and elegant gifts, has enticed maharajahs and kings, business executives and browsers for generations. But for the past decade or so, sales have been so flat that last year the company decided to close six of its seven retail floors and sell only from the main floor of its store at 147 East 57th Street. The fault was the company's, according to its officials. They say their product line, by 1970, had strayed too far from the exclusive and the unusual and included too many items that could be bought most anywhere. The result was that unit sales declined between 1970 and last year, and revenue increases failed even to keep up with inflation. The company declines to talk about its profits or losses in that period.
