aVScientists at General Electric yesterday unveiled one of the smallest functioning devices ever made, a carbon tube about 10 atoms wide that could one day shrink computer chip technology. Researchers at G.E.'s central lab in Niskayuna, N.Y., hope the device, which is a rolled-up sheet of carbon atoms resembling chicken wire, will someday operate as the standard semiconductor in computers and other electronics. The device -- a nanotube -- is part of a developing field of technology used to design devices on the scale of a nanometer, or a billionth of a meter. That translates to about the size of 10 hydrogen atoms, or one-80,000ths the diameter of a human hair. Unlike earlier designs, G.E.'s nanotube can both emit and detect light, the company said. That means it has the potential to perform such tasks as shining small amounts of light on molecules, which have possible applications in medicine or security, said Paul L. McEuen, a physics professor at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y. The next generation of security sensors could be made from such nanotubes, G.E. said, helping detect minuscule amounts of chemical or biological toxins.
p3945
aVInVision Technologies Inc., which is being acquired by General Electric, could face two federal investigations after an internal inquiry showed possible improper payments by distributors tied to sales outside the United States, the company said yesterday. Either company can call off the $900 million purchase if it is not completed by Oct. 31, InVision said in a statement.
