VIn what Washington describes as an attempt to counter countries that unabashedly subsidize their exports, the United States is using funds intended for foreign aid to reduce the price of American exports. About a month ago, the United States allocated $4.2 million, which was to have helped the southern African country of Botswana buy commodities, to reduce the interest rate that Botswana will pay on a loan if it buys locomotives from the General Electric Company or the General Motors Corporation. If Botswana signs the contract for the locomotives, it will get the $4.2 million, which it can apply to the financing costs. This is the first mixed credit - so called because foreign aid is mixed into a loan - that the United States has offered, aside from an experimental program confined by legislation to Egypt.
