aVThe European Commission will take charge of the antitrust assessment of General Electric's acquisition of a unit of Agfa-Gevaert at the request of seven European countries. Germany, Austria, Greece, Ireland, Spain, Portugal and Italy asked the commission to rule on the 400 million euro deal ($475 million). It involves businesses that are too small to set off an automatic review. General Electric agreed in January to buy the Agfa unit, which makes ultrasonic systems to test materials. The commission suspended the normal four-week ruling deadline so it can get information from G.E., a spokesman said.
p4249
aVThe Calpine Corporation, which produces electricity in 23 states, sold a 60 percent stake in a California power plant unit to GE Structured Finance for $82 million to help complete plants under construction. The unit leases and operates the 115-megawatt King City Power Plant in California, Calpine said. The plant produces enough power for 92,000 average homes and is fueled by natural gas. Calpine, which is based in San Jose, Calif., has shed workers, delayed plant projects and sold assets to trim debt and meet expenses after its credit ratings were cut by Moody's Investors Service and Standard & Poor's. GE Structured Finance is part of the GE Commercial Finance unit of the General Electric Company.
